{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = John Edward Fogarty International Center |logo = Logo-Fogarty-International-Center-US-National-Institutes-of-Health-NIH.png |logo_caption = |formed = July 1, 1968 |headquarters = [[Bethesda, Maryland]] |employees = |budget = |chief1_name = |chief1_position = |parent_agency = [[National Institutes of Health]] |website = {{URL|www.fic.nih.gov}} |footnotes = }}
The '''John E. Fogarty International Center''' was founded in 1968 by US President [[Lyndon Johnson]] at the [[National Institutes of Health]] to support international medical and behavioral research and to train international researchers.
==History== On July 1, 1968 President [[Lyndon Johnson]] issued an Executive Order establishing the [[John E. Fogarty]] International Center for Advanced Study in the Health Sciences at the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) in order to support international medical and behavioral research and to train international researchers..<ref>{{cite web|title=Fogarty International Center|url=http://www.fic.nih.gov/|accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref>
In March 2017, the [[Trump Administration]] proposed cuts to the NIH budget, including elimination of the Fogarty Center, saving $69 million.<ref>Donald G. McNeil Jr. [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/17/health/global-health-fogarty-international-center-viruses.html Trump Plan Eliminates a Global Sentinel Against Disease, Experts Warn ] New York Times, 17 March 2017, retrieved 12 July 2018</ref>
